=============== About Fabrix Data Visualization for Splunk ===============
Welcome to Fabrix for Splunk

Introduction

Fabrix has created a revolutionary way to visualize your IT operations by transforming enormous amounts of operational data into actionable information with visual alerts. The visualizations provide a panoramic field of view for IT operations. This allows your team to resolve, remediate and act fast. See events happen in real-time and solve issues before they impact your business. FabrixÕ visualization solution is centralized, allowing all business stakeholders to see a shared context of information and enabling effective communication. This further reduces the time it takes to resolve issues.

-IDENTIFY issues before they impact your customers and your business.
-RESOLVE issues in half the time it takes you today.
-COLLABORATE and communicate more efficiently.
-MAINTAIN IT service levels to meet key performance indicators (KPI).
-REDUCE operational costs.

Installing Fabrix

NOTE: To create fabrix visualizations, after installing the Fabrix splunk app, the Fabrix Web Access component needs to be downloaded and installed from getfabrix.com.

How to install Fabrix

Step 1 => Install Fabrix Splunk app
Step 2 => Go to www.getFabrix.com/register to create an account
Step 3 => Click on 'FREE Fabrix' to download and install Fabrix Web Access Component.
*Documentations and video guides can be found on www.getFabrix.com.

Enjoy Fabrix..!
Fabrix, storyteller for your operation!

#### This application is also officially available on Splunk Base:

https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3251/

Currently, Fabrix for Splunk is only supported on Linux 64bit!!.
Note: Ubuntu is not supported yet.

=============== Splunk SavedSearch ===============
Name: Generate_lookup_for_apps

To visualize Fabrix maps, information about installed Splunk apps is read in.
rest command is used to collect App Title, Label, and Version information then a lookup file is created excluding Add-On, SA-*, sample, TA-*, etc.
This lookup file is used when fabrix generates its maps for visualization.
Users can use the Lookup Editor to choose which apps to include in fabrix visualization.

=============== Splunk Macros ===============
== Macro for generating map information
1 - `get_all_map()` : Main macro for generating fabrix maps. For each map levels, sub-macros are called.

`get_l1_common()` 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ | `get_l2_common()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ | `get_user_defined()` ]


==  Macro for generating metrics for Level 1 maps
1 - `get_l1_status()` : Macro for generating Level 1 maps's metric information. For every object in the map, a sub-macro is called.

`get_paloalto_overview(1, "Fabrix", "overview")` 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_cisco_security_overview(1, "Fabrix", "cisco_security_overview")` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_cisco_firewall_event()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_cisco_wsa_overview()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_bcoat_overview()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_fe_analytics()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_fe_nx_analysis()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l1_fe_ax_visualization()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ | `get_l1_user_metrics()` ] 

== Macro for generating metrics for Level 2 maps
2 - `get_l2_status()` : Macro for generating Level 2 maps's metric information. For every object in the map, a sub-macro is called.

`get_paloalto_overview(2, "SplunkforPaloAltoNetworks", "overview_lv3")` 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_cisco_security_overview(2, "Splunk_CiscoSecuritySuite", "cisco_security_overview_lv3")` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ search `get_l2_cisco_ise_alarm_summary()` ] 
| append maxout=0 maxtime=0 [ | `get_l2_user_metrics()` ] 

=============== Fabrix Support ===============
Restrictions.
Support is delivered in English only unless you are in a location where Fabrix has made localized support available.

Contacts.
Fabrix support provides online documentation, web forum, and email.
Online documentation: http://getfabrix.com/support/documentation
Web forum (answers): http://getfabrix.com/support/answers
Email support: support@getfabrix.com

Priority levels.
P1: Fabrix software is completely inaccessible or the majority of its functionality is unusable.
P2: One or more key features of Fabrix software are unusable.
P3: Any other case where a Fabrix software feature is not operating as documented.
P4: All enhancement requests.

Target fix date or workaround.
P1: 1 day, P2: 1 week, P3: Next release, P4: At discretion

Email status updates
P1: Daily, P2: Weekly, P3: None, P4: None

Support hours.
P1: 24*7
P2: Monday through Friday during standard business hours (9am to 5pm); excluding holiday.
P3: Same above
P4: Same above

Your obligation to assist.
Should you report a purported defect in the software to Fabrix, Fabrix may require you to provide them with the following information:
(a) a general description of the operating environment,
(b) a list of all hardware components, operating systems, and networks,
(c) a reproducible test case, and
(d) any log files, trace and systems files.
Your failure to provide this information may prevent Fabrix from identifying and fixing that purported defect.
